Item ea, quae ex hostibus capimus, iure gentium statim nostra fiunt: adeo quidem, ut et·liberi homines in servitutem nostram deducantur, qui tamen, si evaserint nostram potestatem et ad suos reversi latuerint, pristinum statum recipiunt. Item lapilli gemmae et cetera, quae in litore inveniuntur, iure naturali statim inven- 19 toris fiunt. Item ea, quae ex animalibus dominio tuo subiectis nata sunt, eodem iure tibi adquiruntur.

By eodem iure may be meant either ‘iure naturali' or ‘dominio’ Justinian passes from occupatio to a second title of natural law, viz. accessio, by which is meant the accrual (1) of res nullius or (2) of res alienae to our own property. Each of these heads comprises a number of distinct cases, most of which are known by specific names.
